Space-Time Prediction of Bike Share Demand

Hanzhi Zhang

November 10, 2022

1.Introduction

With the emergence of shared bicycles, more and more problems have arisen in the city regarding shared bicycles. We can see that there are too many bikes taking up the sidewalks in the locations where bikes are parked. There is a shortage of bicycles in locations where there is a high volume of traffic and a need for more bicycles. Therefore, how to allocate shared bikes in a reasonable way has become a research problem for urban researchers.

If we can accurately predict the demand for shared bikes at different times and in different geographical locations, we can maximize the use of these resources. This is both an optimization of urban space and a convenience for bicycle users.

I think the re-balance needs to be done through the bike-sharing companies in conjunction with the city planning department. For bike-sharing companies, they can set up special transfer bicycle staff to carry out bicycle transportation. For example, transferring bikes from stations with low demand to stations with high demand at a certain point in time. For bicycle users, incentives could be provided to encourage them to park their bicycles at “Bonas Points” marked on the map to earn points. Or, a reminder to users which stations have more bikes. Considering the changes in urban traffic I think such a forecast should be in 1 hour to 2 hours increments.

philCensus <- 
  get_acs(geography = "tract", 
          variables = c("B01003_001", "B19013_001", 
                        "B02001_002", "B08013_001",
                        "B08012_001", "B08301_001", 
                        "B08301_010", "B01002_001"), 
          year = 2020, 
          state = "PA", 
          geometry = TRUE, 
          county=c("Philadelphia"),
          output = "wide") %>%
  rename(Total_Pop =  B01003_001E,
         Med_Inc = B19013_001E,
         Med_Age = B01002_001E,
         White_Pop = B02001_002E,
         Travel_Time = B08013_001E,
         Num_Commuters = B08012_001E,
         Means_of_Transport = B08301_001E,
         Total_Public_Trans = B08301_010E) %>%
  select(Total_Pop, Med_Inc, White_Pop, Travel_Time,
         Means_of_Transport, Total_Public_Trans,
         Med_Age,
         GEOID, geometry) %>%
  mutate(Percent_White = White_Pop / Total_Pop,
         Mean_Commute_Time = Travel_Time / Total_Public_Trans,
         Percent_Taking_Public_Trans = Total_Public_Trans / Means_of_Transport)
philTracts <- 
  philCensus %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  distinct(GEOID, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
  select(GEOID, geometry) %>% 
  st_sf
dat_census <- st_join(bikedata %>% 
          filter(is.na(start_lon) == FALSE &
                   is.na(start_lat) == FALSE &
                   is.na(end_lat) == FALSE &
                   is.na(end_lon) == FALSE) %>%
          st_as_sf(., coords = c("start_lon", "start_lat"), crs = 4326),
        philTracts %>%
          st_transform(crs=4326),
        join=st_intersects,
              left = TRUE) %>%
  rename(Origin.Tract = GEOID) %>%
  mutate(start_lon = unlist(map(geometry, 1)),
         start_lat = unlist(map(geometry, 2)))%>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  select(-geometry)%>%
  st_as_sf(., coords = c("end_lon", "end_lat"), crs = 4326) %>%
  st_join(., philTracts %>%
            st_transform(crs=4326),
          join=st_intersects,
          left = TRUE) %>%
  rename(Destination.Tract = GEOID)  %>%
  mutate(end_lon = unlist(map(geometry, 1)),
         end_lat = unlist(map(geometry, 2)))%>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  select(-geometry)

weather.Panel <- 
  riem_measures(station = "PHL", date_start = "2020-04-29", date_end = "2020-06-02") %>%
  dplyr::select(valid, tmpf, p01i, sknt)%>%
  replace(is.na(.), 0) %>%
    mutate(interval60 = ymd_h(substr(valid,1,13))) %>%
    mutate(week = week(interval60),
           dotw = wday(interval60, label=TRUE)) %>%
    group_by(interval60) %>%
    summarize(Temperature = max(tmpf),
              Precipitation = sum(p01i),
              Wind_Speed = max(sknt)) %>%
    mutate(Temperature = ifelse(Temperature == 0, 42, Temperature))

  dat_census %>%
  mutate(Trip_Counter = 1) %>%

3. Create Time lags

Memorial Day in on May 25, 2020. So I select May 25 as the holiday, and select the holiday lag in the model to take holiday influence into account.

yday(as.Date("2020-05-25"))
## [1] 146
ride.panel <- 
  ride.panel %>% 
  arrange(start_station, interval60) %>% 
  mutate(lagHour = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,1),
         lag2Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,2),
         lag3Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,3),
         lag4Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,4),
         lag12Hours = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,12),
         lag1day = dplyr::lag(Trip_Count,24),
         holiday = ifelse(yday(interval60) == 146,1,0)) %>%
   mutate(day = yday(interval60)) %>%
   mutate(holidayLag = case_when(dplyr::lag(holiday, 1) == 1 ~ "PlusOneDay",
                                 dplyr::lag(holiday, 2) == 1 ~ "PlustTwoDays",
                                 dplyr::lag(holiday, 3) == 1 ~ "PlustThreeDays",
                                 dplyr::lead(holiday, 1) == 1 ~ "MinusOneDay",
                                 dplyr::lead(holiday, 2) == 1 ~ "MinusTwoDays",
                                 dplyr::lead(holiday, 3) == 1 ~ "MinusThreeDays"),
         holidayLag = ifelse(is.na(holidayLag) == TRUE, "0", holidayLag))
as.data.frame(ride.panel) %>%
    group_by(interval60) %>% 
    summarise_at(vars(starts_with("lag"), "Trip_Count"), mean, na.rm = TRUE) %>%
    gather(Variable, Value, -interval60, -Trip_Count) %>%
    mutate(Variable = factor(Variable, levels=c("lagHour","lag2Hours","lag3Hours","lag4Hours",
                                                "lag12Hours","lag1day")))%>%
    group_by(Variable) %>%  
    summarize(correlation = round(cor(Value, Trip_Count),2))

4. Run Models

Split data into a training and a test set. The reason why I split the data by time is to avoid separate data. When we talk about data in one day, it should be completed. If we choose random data, bicycle data in a complete day will be separate, which will reduce the accuracy of the model, and there is no way to find the relationship between the independent and dependent variables.

The reason why I use the end of the month is because of the holiday at the end of the month. If I use the data without holiday to train the data, the model can not recognize the holiday predictor.

ride.panel$start_station_name <- 
  as.character(ride.panel$start_station)
ride.Train <- filter(ride.panel, week > 20)
ride.Test <- filter(ride.panel, week <= 20)
reg1 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature,  data=ride.Train)

reg2 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start_station_name + dotw + Temperature,  data=ride.Train)

reg3 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start_station_name + hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature + Precipitation, 
     data=ride.Train)

reg4 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start_station_name +  hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature + Precipitation +
                   lagHour + lag2Hours +lag3Hours + lag12Hours + lag1day, 
     data=ride.Train)

reg5 <- 
  lm(Trip_Count ~  start_station_name + hour(interval60) + dotw + Temperature + Precipitation +
                   lagHour + lag2Hours +lag3Hours +lag12Hours + lag1day + holidayLag + holiday, 
     data=ride.Train)
summary(reg1)

4. Use purr to Predict for test data

ride.Test.weekNest <- 
  ride.Test %>%
  nest(-week) 
model_pred <- function(dat, fit){
   pred <- predict(fit, newdata = dat)}

Don’t use MAPE here is because of the dataset is huge? When we calculate mean absolute percentage error in each time in each point, it will cost a lot of time.

week_predictions <- 
  ride.Test.weekNest %>% 
    mutate(ATime_FE = map(.x = data, fit = reg1, .f = model_pred),
           BSpace_FE = map(.x = data, fit = reg2, .f = model_pred),
           CTime_Space_FE = map(.x = data, fit = reg3, .f = model_pred),
           DTime_Space_FE_timeLags = map(.x = data, fit = reg4, .f = model_pred),
           ETime_Space_FE_timeLags_holidayLags = map(.x = data, fit = reg5, .f = model_pred)) %>% 
    gather(Regression, Prediction, -data, -week) %>%
    mutate(Observed = map(data, pull, Trip_Count),
           Absolute_Error = map2(Observed, Prediction,  ~ abs(.x - .y)),
           MAE = map_dbl(Absolute_Error, mean, na.rm = TRUE),
           sd_AE = map_dbl(Absolute_Error, sd, na.rm = TRUE))

1. Examine Error Metrics for Accuracy

The result of MAPE of each model shows the fourth model performs better because it has a lower MAPE in every week. It is surprising that the holidaylags model performs worse than the fourth one. The reason I think is maybe the holiday (especially memorial day) has no influence on people using sharing-bike, or the length of holiday lag should be adjusted.

## 3. LOGO-CV

I use the LOGO-CV to check the stability of the model, and the result shows a big peak and concentration. I think the result is not bad, which shows the model is consistent. But there is an outline in the model, I check the station is the location(39.96439,-75.17987)–Philadelphia Museum of Art.

regvariable <- c("dotw", "Temperature", "Precipitation", "lagHour", "lag2Hours", "lag3Hours", "lag12Hours",  "lag1day", "holiday", "holidayLag")

crossValidate <- function(dataset, id, dependentVariable, indVariables) {
  allPredictions <- data.frame()
  cvID_list <- unique(dataset[[id]])
  
  for (i in cvID_list) {
    
    thisFold <- i
    
    fold.train <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] != thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
      dplyr::select(id, indVariables, dependentVariable)
    fold.test  <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] == thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
      dplyr::select(id, indVariables, dependentVariable)
    
    regression <-
      glm(Trip_Count ~ ., family = "poisson", 
          data = fold.train %>% 
            dplyr::select(-id))
    
    thisPrediction <- 
      mutate(fold.test, Prediction = predict(regression, fold.test, type = "response"))
    
    allPredictions <-
      rbind(allPredictions, thisPrediction)
    
  }
  return(allPredictions)
}


reg.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = ride.panel,
  id = "start_station",
  dependentVariable = "Trip_Count",
  indVariables = regvariable) %>%
  dplyr::select(cvID = start_station, Trip_Count, Prediction)

reg.summary <- mutate(reg.cv, Error = Prediction - Trip_Count,
                      Regression = "cross validation on the 5 week panel")

error_by_reg_and_fold <- 
  reg.summary %>%
  group_by(Regression, cvID) %>% 
  summarize(Mean_Error = mean(Prediction - Trip_Count, na.rm = T),
            MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T),
            SD_MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T)) %>%
  ungroup()
error_by_reg_and_fold.long <-
  error_by_reg_and_fold%>%
  gather(Vriable, Value, -cvID, -Regression)%>%
  unnest()
ggplot(error_by_reg_and_fold.long, aes(x = Value)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 100, fill = "Black") +
  facet_wrap(~Vriable, ncol = 3, scales = "free")

5. Result

In this model, the places with higher MAE values are mainly concentrated in the city center and localized points. And the underestimation of bicycle demand can lead to people not having enough bicycle sharing at some stations. The degradation of user experience may lead to the loss of users, and the lack of enough bikes may lead to problems such as road traffic congestion.

I think it is possible to perform a spatial correlation analysis of moran’s I on ERROR values and investigate which independent variables these spatial distributions are related to. In the future, some spatial lag can be added to the model to reduce the error.

According to outliner–Philadelphia Museum of Art, I think we can add art venues or large public buildings to the model prediction. This is because they may not be walkable or easily accessible by car due to their surroundings: large green areas or open spaces.
